00:33:50.080 --> 00:33:52.160
that you won't be
able to measure it.

00:33:52.160 --> 00:33:54.880
So what we're going to be
doing is sticking your samples

00:33:54.880 --> 00:33:57.730
into the reactor for
maybe an hour or so,

00:33:57.730 --> 00:33:59.920
pulling them out, and
immediately running them over

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:03.498
to the detector, so that we get
the most signal per unit time.

00:34:03.498 --> 00:34:06.040
Because the things are going to
be the hottest when they come

00:34:06.040 --> 00:34:09.219
right out of the reactor,
and every second you lose

00:34:09.219 --> 00:34:11.020
from there you lose signal.

00:34:11.020 --> 00:34:13.090
Which means you have
to account for longer

00:34:13.090 --> 00:34:14.980
to get the same
amount of information

00:34:14.980 --> 00:34:16.397
with the same certainty.

00:34:16.397 --> 00:34:17.980
This is a nice segue
way to what we'll

00:34:17.980 --> 00:34:21.130
be talking about Thursday
which is statistics, certainty,

00:34:21.130 --> 00:34:22.270
and precision.

00:34:22.270 --> 00:34:24.639
How long do you have
to count something

00:34:24.639 --> 00:34:27.760
to be confident
within some interval

00:34:27.760 --> 00:34:30.000
that you've got the
correct activity?

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:34.730
For background counts-- who here
is made a NSC Geiger counter?

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:36.080
Hopefully almost all of you.

00:34:36.080 --> 00:34:37.580
Maybe you guys
remember how long you

00:34:37.580 --> 00:34:40.980
had to count to be 95% sure
that your background rate was

00:34:40.980 --> 00:34:42.870
accurate.

00:34:42.870 --> 00:34:46.510
It ends up being about 67
minutes or over an hour,

00:34:46.510 --> 00:34:49.040
and the reason is because
the count rate is very low.

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:51.460
So I'll do a little
flash forward to Thursday

00:34:51.460 --> 00:34:53.380
since we're talking about it.

00:34:53.380 --> 00:34:56.080
When you count something
with a very low count rate,

00:34:56.080 --> 00:34:58.750
you have to account for
longer to be as confident

00:34:58.750 --> 00:35:00.470
that your number is correct.

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:03.460
So let's say you want
to be 95% confident

00:35:03.460 --> 00:35:07.120
or within plus or minus 2
standard deviations or 2 sigma.

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:09.340
You have to count for
longer and longer.

00:35:09.340 --> 00:35:10.990
For something that's
really radioactive

00:35:10.990 --> 00:35:14.590
you can be sure, or 95%
sure, that the count

00:35:14.590 --> 00:35:18.010
rate you measured is accurate
for a shorter counting time.

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:20.480
So everything in this class
seems to come up in trade-offs.

00:35:20.480 --> 00:35:20.980
Right?

00:35:20.980 --> 00:35:23.530
You trade off stability
for a half-life.

00:35:23.530 --> 00:35:26.200
You trade off decay
constant for half-life.

00:35:26.200 --> 00:35:29.220
You trade off binding
energy for excess mass.

00:35:29.220 --> 00:35:32.880
You trade off counting
time and precision.

00:35:32.880 --> 00:35:34.830
You trade off exposure
and dose. which

00:35:34.830 --> 00:35:36.550
you're going to get into later.

00:35:36.550 --> 00:35:38.710
We'll see if anyone
wants to use a cell phone

00:35:38.710 --> 00:35:40.690
or eat irradiated
food afterwards.

00:35:40.690 --> 00:35:44.470
And I do all the time, so that
